pull_request.title: Add comprehensive GitHub Copilot instructions for Lamdera Elm development
pull_request.body:
This PR adds a comprehensive `.github/copilot-instructions.md` file that provides GitHub Copilot coding agents with detailed, validated instructions for working effectively in this Lamdera-based Elm accounting application.

## Key Features

**Exhaustively Validated Commands**: Every single command and workflow has been tested and timed to ensure reliability:
- Frontend/Backend compilation: ~30 seconds cold, <1 second warm
- Development server startup: ~45 seconds cold, <5 seconds warm  
- Code formatting and linting workflows

**Critical Timing Guidelines**: Includes explicit "NEVER CANCEL" warnings with specific timeout recommendations:
- Build commands: 60+ second timeouts for cold builds
- Server startup: 120+ second timeouts for initial launches
- All timing measurements based on actual test runs

**Complete Development Workflow**: Covers the full development lifecycle from initial setup through validation:
- Initial setup with Node.js 20 and Lamdera CLI installation
- Core build commands for Frontend and Backend modules
- Development server operation and validation
- Pre-commit validation checklist

**Manual Testing Requirements**: Emphasizes the critical importance of functional validation after code changes, including:
- HTTP response verification (`curl` commands provided)
- Complete user scenario testing requirements
- Application accessibility validation

**Project-Specific Guidance**: Tailored specifically for this Lamdera Elm application:
- Explains the Evergreen migration system for type changes
- Documents the unified full-stack development approach
- Covers Lamdera-specific deployment considerations
- Includes troubleshooting for common Lamdera issues

**Comprehensive Reference**: Provides detailed project structure documentation, expected command outputs, and troubleshooting guidance to minimize the need for additional context gathering.

The instructions follow an imperative tone throughout and prioritize known-working validation steps to ensure agents can work efficiently and reliably in this codebase.

Fixes #17.

issue.body:
Bumps [@astrojs/sitemap](https://github.com/withastro/astro/tree/HEAD/packages/integrations/sitemap) from 3.4.2 to 3.5.0.
Release notes

Sourced from @â€‹astrojs/sitemap's releases.

@â€‹astrojs/sitemap@â€‹3.5.0

Minor Changes

  • #13682 5824b32 Thanks @â€‹gouravkhunger! - Adds a customSitemaps option to include extra sitemaps in the sitemap-index.xml file generated by Astro.

    This is useful for multi-framework setups on the same domain as your Astro site (example.com), such as a blog at example.com/blog whose sitemap is generated by another framework.

    The following example shows configuring your Astro site to include sitemaps for an externally-generated blog and help center along with the generated sitemap entries in sitemap-index.xml:

    Example:

    import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config';
import sitemap from '@astrojs/sitemap';

    export default defineConfig({
site: 'https://example.com',
integrations: [
sitemap({
customSitemaps: [
'https://example.com/blog/sitemap.xml',
'https://example.com/helpcenter/sitemap.xml',
],
}),
],
});

    Learn more in the @astrojs/sitemap configuration documentation.

issue.body:
Signed-off-by: Igor Bezukh <ibezukh@redhat.com>

Runbook PR: https://github.com/openshift/runbooks/pull/318

**What this PR does / why we need it**:
In an upgrade scenario it can happen that duplicate wasp-agent
deployment can appear, since previous wasp-agent deployments
were manual and in a different namespace.
Therefore in order to make sure the user is aware of it we
are adding an alert which will rely on the a metric of memory
overcommit percentage and presence of wasp namespace.


**Reviewer Checklist**

> Reviewers are supposed to review the PR for every aspect below one by one. To check an item means the PR is either "OK" or "Not Applicable" in terms of that item. All items are supposed to be checked before merging a PR.

- [ ] Functional Tests
- [ ] User Documentation

- [ ] Upgrade Scenario
- [ ] Uninstallation Scenario
- [ ] Backward Compatibility
- [ ] Troubleshooting Friendly

```jira-ticket
https://issues.redhat.com/browse/CNV-57781
```

**Release note**:
<!--  Write your release note:
1. Enter your extended release note in the below block. If the PR requires additional action from users switching to the new release, include the string "action required".

```release-note
Add Prometheus alert for detecting duplicate wasp-agent deployment
```

issue.title: Tab "folders" automatically enables
issue.body:
### Checklist

- [x] I am able to reproduce the bug with the [latest debug version](https://github.com/OuterTune/OuterTune/actions) AND any logs I have attached are taken with the DEBUG version (NOT release).
- [x] I've checked that there is no open or closed issue about this bug. [CHECK THE ISSUE TRACKER HERE](https://github.com/OuterTune/OuterTune/issues)
- [x] This issue contains only one bug.
- [x] The title of this issue accurately describes the bug.
- [ ] I've checked these boxes without reading carefully.

### Steps to reproduce the bug

1. Disable tab "folders"
2. Go to tab "library"
3. Enable filter "folders"
4. Click "local scanner"
5. Tab "folders" automatically enables

### Expected behavior

Don't enable any tabs automatically

### Actual behavior

Tab "folders" automatically enables, when I open settings page "local media"

### Screenshots/Screen recordings

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1ba1f83d-926b-4294-bd2b-5b6d93700c2f

### Logs

Sorry, but I'm lazy :)

### OuterTune version

0.9.3

### Device & Android version

Poco M6 Pro 4G, Android 15

### Additional information

I don't want to use tab "folders", because I have its functionality in library with filter "folders".

P.s.: Sorry if my English is bad...
